1
00:00:04,000 --> 00:00:08,963
The Non-Cooperation Movement witnessed unprecedented participation

2
00:00:09,063 --> 00:00:11,725
from all sections of Indian society.

3
00:00:12,400 --> 00:00:16,382
Students left government schools and colleges in large numbers,

4
00:00:16,482 --> 00:00:20,400
leading to the establishment of national schools and colleges.

5
00:00:21,600 --> 00:00:25,413
Lawyers like Motilal Nehru, C.R. Das, and others gave up

6
00:00:25,513 --> 00:00:30,025
their lucrative practices and refused to appear in British courts.

7
00:00:31,266 --> 00:00:34,574
Government employees resigned from their posts, and

8
00:00:34,674 --> 00:00:38,516
people began boycotting British goods, especially textiles.

9
00:00:39,800 --> 00:00:43,260
The movement saw massive bonfires of foreign cloth,

10
00:00:43,360 --> 00:00:46,612
and Indians embraced khadi or hand-spun cloth as

11
00:00:46,712 --> 00:00:49,475
a symbol of self-reliance and resistance.

12
00:00:50,666 --> 00:00:54,559
The movement also gained support from various communities -

13
00:00:54,659 --> 00:00:58,349
Muslims joined due to the Khilafat issue, while peasants

14
00:00:58,449 --> 00:01:02,816
and workers participated to protest against economic exploitation.

15
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:08,300
The Indian National Congress, under Gandhi's leadership, became

16
00:01:08,400 --> 00:01:11,025
a mass organization for the first time.

